00:00:25.732 --> 00:00:26.760
PROFESSOR: I.e.

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:30.090
When multiple lineages
of beneficial mutants

00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:32.790
are kind of spreading in a
population at the same time,

00:00:32.790 --> 00:00:34.660
so when these clones
are somehow interfering

00:00:34.660 --> 00:00:36.550
with each other
in the population,

00:00:36.550 --> 00:00:39.110
how is it that that
clonal interference effect

00:00:39.110 --> 00:00:42.035
kind of plays out in the context
of these microbial asexual

00:00:42.035 --> 00:00:42.535
populations.

00:00:42.535 --> 00:00:45.720
And in particular,
in this paper, what

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:48.700
they were trying to measure
was the distribution of effects

00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:50.390
of beneficial mutations.

00:00:50.390 --> 00:00:53.650
So you've put a population
into some new environment.

00:00:53.650 --> 00:00:56.540
There may be some beneficial
mutations that are possible.

00:00:56.540 --> 00:00:59.270
The question is, what is
the probability distribution

00:00:59.270 --> 00:01:01.732
of effects of those
beneficial mutations.

00:01:01.732 --> 00:01:04.000
And this is, as
you might imagine,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.460
a very basic quantitative
we'd like to understand just

00:01:07.460 --> 00:01:10.574
to understand how evolution
works in new environments.

00:01:10.574 --> 00:01:11.990
But it's actually
something that's

00:01:11.990 --> 00:01:13.156
rather difficult to measure.

00:01:13.156 --> 00:01:15.130
And what's interesting
here is it's

00:01:15.130 --> 00:01:20.960
difficult to measure for
maybe a surprising reason.

00:01:20.960 --> 00:01:26.160
This is a wonderful example
of how you kind of-- if life

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:28.370
gives you lemons,
then make lemonade.

00:01:28.370 --> 00:01:30.066
Is that the expression?

00:01:30.066 --> 00:01:30.953
OK.

00:01:30.953 --> 00:01:31.452
All right.

00:01:31.452 --> 00:01:34.090
So in this paper, they
set out to try and measure

00:01:34.090 --> 00:01:37.450
the [? distribution ?] effects
of beneficial mutations.

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:39.227
They were unsuccessful.

00:01:39.227 --> 00:01:41.435
But they were unsuccessful
for an interesting reason,

00:01:41.435 --> 00:01:43.336
so then they were able
to write what I think

00:01:43.336 --> 00:01:47.304
is a very nice science paper.

00:01:47.304 --> 00:01:50.215
Are there any
questions about where

00:01:50.215 --> 00:01:52.590
we are or administrative
things before we get going?

00:01:57.340 --> 00:02:01.610
All right, so just to recap
where we were from last time,

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:03.990
we introduced this
Moran model, which

00:02:03.990 --> 00:02:06.650
there's a fixed
population size, N.

00:02:06.650 --> 00:02:10.650
Then each of these sort
of cycles, what we do

00:02:10.650 --> 00:02:14.210
is we choose one
individual to divide

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:17.725
and we choose one
individual to be replaced.

00:02:17.725 --> 00:02:23.830
And we have the daughter, say,
cell replace the cell that

00:02:23.830 --> 00:02:26.150
was chosen for replacement.

00:02:26.150 --> 00:02:28.690
Now in that model,
what we found was

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:31.560
that there's some
probability, x1,

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:33.500
for a new mutant with
relative fitness,

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:37.040
r, to actually fix
in the population.

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:41.850
And this is in the case
of no clonal interference.

00:02:41.850 --> 00:02:45.740
So CI will in general be
clonal interference today.

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:50.170
So this is-- if it's
just this one mutation

00:02:50.170 --> 00:02:54.590
that we're considering, then
the question of surviving

00:02:54.590 --> 00:02:56.750
stochastic extinction
kind of at the beginning

00:02:56.750 --> 00:03:00.190
is equivalent to the
question of being

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:03.610
able to fix in the
population certainly

00:03:03.610 --> 00:03:07.490
for a beneficial mutation,
with r greater than 1.

00:03:07.490 --> 00:03:09.360
So what we want to do
today to just start

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:11.890
is to try to think
about how we can

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:14.980
use this model and
this equation in order

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:17.578
to understand the
probability of fixation

00:03:17.578 --> 00:03:19.744
when there's more than one
mutant in the population.

00:03:22.780 --> 00:03:27.080
So here, what we found
is that this thing,

00:03:27.080 --> 00:03:31.730
there are 2 limits that we
might want to keep track of.

00:03:31.730 --> 00:03:41.020
So this thing goes to 1 over
n, for neutral mutations,

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:47.470
and it goes to S for moderately
beneficial mutations.

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:57.140
So S is defined as r minus 1.

00:03:57.140 --> 00:03:58.990
So it's this for
S kind of greater

00:03:58.990 --> 00:04:04.145
than zero, and for S times
n, much larger than 1.

00:04:11.210 --> 00:04:13.756
So I guess this already says
that S is greater than zero,

00:04:13.756 --> 00:04:14.755
so we could ignore that.

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:20.779
Are there any questions
about this before we

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:26.075
get going to practice using it?

00:04:26.075 --> 00:04:29.440
All right, so I just
wanted to have us consider

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:31.365
a few possible situations.

00:04:35.138 --> 00:04:37.480
All right, population size 10.

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:39.290
What we want to consider
a situation where

00:04:39.290 --> 00:04:40.550
there are two mutants.

00:04:44.414 --> 00:04:49.760
And we're going to call them A
and B, with relative fitness rA

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:55.315
1.01, and rB 0.99.

00:04:55.315 --> 00:05:00.030
So A is a beneficial mutant,
and B is a deleterious mutant.

00:05:00.030 --> 00:05:01.640
And in all these
problems, we're going

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:05.740
to assume that the rest of
the population has fitness 1.

00:05:05.740 --> 00:05:08.114
So these fitnesses
of A and B, they

00:05:08.114 --> 00:05:10.030
are as compared to the
rest of the population.

00:05:10.030 --> 00:05:11.680
So in this case, there are
eight other individuals

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:12.765
with relative fitness 1.

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:19.340
So the question is, what is
the probability that a fixes.

00:05:26.450 --> 00:05:27.950
Takes over the population.

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:32.120
Reaches number of A
individuals equal to 10.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:34.800
At that stage, we're not
allowing for any new mutations

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:36.765
here, so then that's
the end of the dynamics.

00:05:40.212 --> 00:05:41.670
So you can start
thinking about it,

00:05:41.670 --> 00:05:43.980
and I will give
some options here.

00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:10.619
All right so this is
in the Moran model,

00:06:10.619 --> 00:06:12.160
what is the probability
that A fixes.

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:22.028
I'll give you 20 seconds
to think about it.

00:06:43.950 --> 00:06:45.460
Do you need more time?

00:06:51.314 --> 00:06:53.230
Let's go ahead and vote,
and see where we are.

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:53.840
Ready.

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:56.165
Three, two, one--

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:06.100
All right, we got some-- I'd
say Bs, Cs is kind of dominant.

00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:06.900
All right.

00:07:06.900 --> 00:07:10.150
So I'd say that there's
generally a disagreement

00:07:10.150 --> 00:07:14.852
between B and C. Interesting.

00:07:14.852 --> 00:07:16.320
OK.

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:18.520
I think that there's--
it's almost 50/50.

00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:20.700
It is a bit splotchy, somehow.

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:24.135
You may need to make some effort
to find somebody that disagrees

00:07:24.135 --> 00:07:25.260
with you, but please do so.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:27.510
All right, turn to a neighbor
and try to convince them

00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:30.716
that you're right.

00:07:30.716 --> 00:07:34.684
[SIDE CONVERSATIONS]

00:08:36.218 --> 00:08:39.194
PROFESSOR: All right, let's
go ahead and reconvene and see

00:08:39.194 --> 00:08:42.250
if anybody [INAUDIBLE].

00:08:42.250 --> 00:08:43.200
Ready.

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:47.692
Three, two, one.

00:08:47.692 --> 00:08:49.580
All right.

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:51.660
I'd say that there's
some migration towards C,

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:56.170
but it's not all the way.

00:08:56.170 --> 00:08:58.320
All right, different arguments.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:03.024
And you may want to-- D is the
argument to be made over here.

00:09:03.024 --> 00:09:04.190
All right, so let's hear it.

00:09:04.190 --> 00:09:05.160
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:06.618
So if there's one
individual from A

00:09:06.618 --> 00:09:09.764
and one individual from
B, and basically they're

00:09:09.764 --> 00:09:12.250
about the same fitness,
then the probability

00:09:12.250 --> 00:09:15.729
that they should, I
guess, take over is 50%.

00:09:15.729 --> 00:09:18.214
Well that assumes that one
of them will take over.

00:09:18.214 --> 00:09:18.936
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
is there any reason

00:09:18.936 --> 00:09:20.769
to assume that one of
them should take over?

00:09:20.769 --> 00:09:22.687
AUDIENCE: No.

00:09:22.687 --> 00:09:25.120
PROFESSOR: I think that we
may agree that the probability

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:27.105
that A fixes is going
to be approximately

00:09:27.105 --> 00:09:29.249
equal to the probability
that B fixes.

00:09:29.249 --> 00:09:30.748
That's going to be
a useful insight.

00:09:30.748 --> 00:09:32.740
But [INAUDIBLE]
both those things.

00:09:32.740 --> 00:09:34.732
So we have to keep
track of that.

00:09:34.732 --> 00:09:38.995
So that's the argument
for why it's not D.

00:09:38.995 --> 00:09:40.210
AUDIENCE: You're welcome.

00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:42.420
PROFESSOR: Anytime. [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:42.420 --> 00:09:46.590
So between B and C, how
can we think about this?

00:09:49.415 --> 00:09:51.540
You can tell us once again
what your neighbor said.

00:09:51.540 --> 00:09:52.040
That's fine.

00:09:52.040 --> 00:09:52.726
AUDIENCE: Why?

00:09:52.726 --> 00:09:53.350
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:09:53.350 --> 00:09:57.495
AUDIENCE: Um, well, my
neighbor, as opposed to me,

00:09:57.495 --> 00:10:01.068
made the correct decision to try
to think about it intuitively

00:10:01.068 --> 00:10:02.984
instead of trying to get
through all the math.

00:10:02.984 --> 00:10:03.764
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:10:03.764 --> 00:10:05.930
Always good to think about
things intuitively rather

00:10:05.930 --> 00:10:07.090
than-- that's--

00:10:07.090 --> 00:10:08.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:11.210
So A is very
slightly beneficial,

00:10:11.210 --> 00:10:14.910
and so it is just
a little bit more

00:10:14.910 --> 00:10:17.392
likely to fix than
a neutral mutation.

00:10:17.392 --> 00:10:21.110
PROFESSOR: OK, and how can
we quantify this statement?

00:10:21.110 --> 00:10:23.486
That I know I said that I
didn't like math, but you know,

00:10:23.486 --> 00:10:25.151
every now and then
we should look at it.

00:10:25.151 --> 00:10:27.380
Yeah, so this statement
that A is approximately

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:29.130
a neutral mutation.

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:31.878
How is it that we can--
how do we know that?

00:10:31.878 --> 00:10:32.832
I mean did--

00:10:32.832 --> 00:10:35.217
AUDIENCE: We have criteria
for nearly neutral.

00:10:35.217 --> 00:10:37.580
PROFESSOR: Yes, we have a
criteria for nearly neutral.

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:39.913
What does that-- what does
it mean to be nearly neutral?

00:10:39.913 --> 00:10:42.632
AUDIENCE: The
magnitude of S times N

00:10:42.632 --> 00:10:44.361
is much, much less than one.

00:10:44.361 --> 00:10:45.360
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:48.360
S times N is much
less than one, which

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:50.690
means that it's nearly neutral.

00:10:50.690 --> 00:10:53.180
What that means is that
the probability of fixing

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:56.610
is the same as if it
were a neutral mutation,

00:10:56.610 --> 00:10:59.218
or approximately the same.

00:10:59.218 --> 00:11:01.548
And is that the case here?

00:11:01.548 --> 00:11:02.480
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:11:02.480 --> 00:11:03.412
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:11:03.412 --> 00:11:06.460
S is 0.01, so 1/100.

00:11:06.460 --> 00:11:07.780
N is 10.

00:11:07.780 --> 00:11:11.660
So S times N is equal to 0.1.

00:11:11.660 --> 00:11:15.212
Which means that both-- so
A is maybe nearly neutral.

00:11:15.212 --> 00:11:16.045
Is B nearly neutral?

00:11:16.045 --> 00:11:16.740
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:19.430
PROFESSOR: Yes, so both A
and B are nearly neutral.

00:11:19.430 --> 00:11:22.110
One of them is an advantageous
mutant, one is a deleterious.

00:11:22.110 --> 00:11:24.390
But in this
population size, they

00:11:24.390 --> 00:11:27.420
both behave as if
they're nearly neutral.

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:29.110
But in a larger
population, so if

00:11:29.110 --> 00:11:30.245
we had a million
individuals, would these

00:11:30.245 --> 00:11:31.119
be neutral mutations?

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:31.706
AUDIENCE: No.

00:11:31.706 --> 00:11:33.840
PROFESSOR: No.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:36.110
So the question of
whether something behaves

00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:39.021
as a neutral mutation depends
upon the population size

00:11:39.021 --> 00:11:40.360
via this relation.

00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:47.345
So that's-- and then
how do we go from there?

00:11:47.345 --> 00:11:52.676
AUDIENCE: Well the probability
of a neutral mutation

00:11:52.676 --> 00:11:54.946
[INAUDIBLE] population
is going to be [? 1/S ?].

00:11:54.946 --> 00:11:55.946
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:11:55.946 --> 00:11:58.786
A neutral mutation will fix
a probability of one group.

00:11:58.786 --> 00:12:02.540
So indeed, we're
going to get this.

00:12:02.540 --> 00:12:05.950
And we need to
highlight that we can--

00:12:05.950 --> 00:12:08.510
you have to be very careful
about just sticking things

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:09.530
into formulas.

00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:12.460
So you may remember
that the probability

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:17.050
of a beneficial mutant fixing
in the population is S.

00:12:17.050 --> 00:12:19.750
But that's only for S times
N being much larger than one,

00:12:19.750 --> 00:12:22.700
and that's when there's
no clonal interference.

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:25.200
When you don't have to compete
with other beneficial mutants

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:26.810
in the lineage.

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:28.963
We're going to see an
example of this in a moment.

00:12:28.963 --> 00:12:30.463
But if you just
have a single mutant

00:12:30.463 --> 00:12:34.900
in the population, that's
beneficial in the sense of it's

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:36.390
not neutral.

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:37.740
Then probably the fixation is S.

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:40.420
And of course, this
is nonsensical, right?

00:12:40.420 --> 00:12:43.790
Because you can't--
it wouldn't make any--

00:12:43.790 --> 00:12:45.990
certainly it wouldn't--
given that you say oh well,

00:12:45.990 --> 00:12:48.448
if it were neutral, it would
fix with a probability of 10%.

00:12:48.448 --> 00:12:50.920
And then you say oh, but if
it's an advantageous mutant,

00:12:50.920 --> 00:12:54.776
it can't fix with a
probability less than that.

00:12:54.776 --> 00:12:58.142
So this is nearly neutral,
fixation probability is 10%.

00:12:58.142 --> 00:12:59.975
Are there any questions
about that argument?

00:13:04.725 --> 00:13:09.141
So let's consider a
different problem.

00:13:09.141 --> 00:13:12.943
So now, we're going to consider
a population that's larger.

00:13:12.943 --> 00:13:14.949
So it's going to be the
same situation, where

00:13:14.949 --> 00:13:19.928
we have these two mutants
present as single individuals.

00:13:28.401 --> 00:13:30.900
So what we want to know now is
the probability that B fixes.

00:13:37.261 --> 00:13:39.260
Once again, you should
start thinking about this

00:13:39.260 --> 00:13:43.590
while I type it.

00:13:43.590 --> 00:13:45.200
Oh, there was one
other thing I wanted

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:47.980
to say, actually, over here.

00:13:47.980 --> 00:13:52.410
If we modeled these
population dynamics

00:13:52.410 --> 00:13:57.240
using differential equations--
so instead of doing the Moran

00:13:57.240 --> 00:14:00.692
process where we stochastic
dynamics of division,

00:14:00.692 --> 00:14:03.150
replacement, and so forth, if
you write down a differential

00:14:03.150 --> 00:14:07.720
equation describing
this situation,

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:09.277
what is the probability
that A fixes?

00:14:09.277 --> 00:14:10.735
I'm going to give
you five seconds.

00:14:10.735 --> 00:14:11.556
AUDIENCE: One.

00:14:11.556 --> 00:14:14.532
PROFESSOR: All right, one.

00:14:14.532 --> 00:14:16.516
OK, so you don't get to vote.

00:14:16.516 --> 00:14:20.062
Indeed, 1.

00:14:20.062 --> 00:14:22.270
So if you had written down
the differential equation,

00:14:22.270 --> 00:14:25.360
then there's no
randomness there.

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:28.480
Whichever mutant has
the largest fitness

00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:31.535
will fix with probability 1.

00:14:31.535 --> 00:14:32.035
OK?

00:14:35.602 --> 00:14:36.810
OK, probability that B fixes.

00:15:09.470 --> 00:15:11.260
So this-- you show
me both [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:13.870 --> 00:15:16.541
I'll give you 20, 30
seconds to think about this.

00:15:27.425 --> 00:15:27.925
Yes?

00:15:27.925 --> 00:15:31.066
AUDIENCE: Is there
just one [INAUDIBLE]?

00:15:31.066 --> 00:15:32.950
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:35.250
All right, so this kind
of-- that's why-- yeah.

00:15:35.250 --> 00:15:36.416
So it's just the same thing.

00:15:36.416 --> 00:15:42.420
And so that's a single A
mutant and a single B mutant.

00:15:42.420 --> 00:15:49.298
Single A, single
B. But you should

00:15:49.298 --> 00:15:52.072
know how to calculate these
things if I tell you that they

00:15:52.072 --> 00:15:53.030
were some other number.

00:16:09.214 --> 00:16:10.130
Do you need more time?

00:16:16.804 --> 00:16:19.470
So in general, if you don't look
at me when I ask that question,

00:16:19.470 --> 00:16:20.840
I'm going to take that as
meaning that you're still

00:16:20.840 --> 00:16:21.640
thinking about it.

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:23.196
Is that how I should
interpret that?

00:16:23.196 --> 00:16:23.696
OK.

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:50.930
Let's go ahead and vote just so
that we can see where we are.

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:52.270
OK, ready.

00:16:52.270 --> 00:16:54.550
Three, two, one.

00:16:58.486 --> 00:17:00.500
All right.

