PROFESSOR: Yeah, so that is a
result of clonal interference,

00:48:23.010 --> 00:48:27.990
because it's saying that that
half arises because B, maybe,

00:48:27.990 --> 00:48:30.900
if it did survive, it may
still get out-competed by A.

00:48:30.900 --> 00:48:33.083
So that's clonal interference.

00:48:33.083 --> 00:48:35.166
AUDIENCE: Did you say the
populations of mutations

00:48:35.166 --> 00:48:36.532
weren't [? correct? ?]

00:48:36.532 --> 00:48:37.240
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:48:37.240 --> 00:48:39.390
So the idea is that they
don't interact initially.

00:48:39.390 --> 00:48:42.000
Because when the mutations
are present at a very low

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:44.660
frequency, then they're
really interacting

00:48:44.660 --> 00:48:49.010
with the bulk, the rest of the
population, 10 to the 6 there.

00:48:49.010 --> 00:48:50.970
However, if they survive
stochastic extinction

00:48:50.970 --> 00:48:53.020
and they start spreading
in the population,

00:48:53.020 --> 00:48:56.998
then there's the possibility
of clonal interference.

00:48:56.998 --> 00:49:00.097
AUDIENCE: But wouldn't that
change that [INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:00.097 --> 00:49:00.680
PROFESSOR: No.

00:49:00.680 --> 00:49:04.800
I think that's why
it's at the half.

00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:07.150
Because this factor of a
half is really just saying

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:10.250
that even if B survives
stochastic extinction,

00:49:10.250 --> 00:49:12.270
it only has a 50-50
shot of actually being

00:49:12.270 --> 00:49:15.037
able to take over, because
there's a 50% chance

00:49:15.037 --> 00:49:16.870
it's going to experience
clonal interference

00:49:16.870 --> 00:49:18.994
with this A lineage that's
going to out-compete it.

00:49:26.770 --> 00:49:30.971
Maybe if you're unhappy
about that statement,

00:49:30.971 --> 00:49:31.845
harass me afterwards.

00:49:36.050 --> 00:49:39.060
So from this
discussion, though, how

00:49:39.060 --> 00:49:40.642
can we think about
the importance

00:49:40.642 --> 00:49:41.600
of clonal interference?

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:45.670
In particular, there are
going to be two time scales.

00:49:45.670 --> 00:49:47.149
And the question
of whether there's

00:49:47.149 --> 00:49:48.940
going to be significant
clonal interference

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:53.070
is related to which of
these time scales is larger.

00:49:53.070 --> 00:49:54.975
So what might the
time scales be?

00:50:12.507 --> 00:50:13.965
Or at least one of
the time scales?

00:50:18.676 --> 00:50:20.217
AUDIENCE: I guess
one should probably

00:50:20.217 --> 00:50:21.952
be the time to be established.

00:50:21.952 --> 00:50:22.660
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:50:22.660 --> 00:50:24.270
To be established.

00:50:24.270 --> 00:50:26.914
AUDIENCE: To reach the
[INAUDIBLE] [? establish. ?]

00:50:26.914 --> 00:50:27.580
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:50:33.405 --> 00:50:37.210
So the actual time that it takes
from when a mutation appears

00:50:37.210 --> 00:50:42.600
to when it becomes established--
I mean, there is a time there.

00:50:42.600 --> 00:50:45.540
But it ends up not being
the relevant thing,

00:50:45.540 --> 00:50:48.130
because that's the regime
where they're not actually

00:50:48.130 --> 00:50:50.550
interacting, that the
mutant lineages are not

00:50:50.550 --> 00:50:52.030
interacting anyways.

00:50:52.030 --> 00:50:53.950
So there's a sense
that it doesn't quite

00:50:53.950 --> 00:50:58.206
matter how long that takes,
at least to first order.

00:50:58.206 --> 00:51:03.036
AUDIENCE: How much time did it
take to reach some population

00:51:03.036 --> 00:51:06.132
size [INAUDIBLE]?

00:51:06.132 --> 00:51:06.840
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:51:06.840 --> 00:51:07.680
OK, yeah.

00:51:07.680 --> 00:51:09.380
So one of them is
going to be that it's

00:51:09.380 --> 00:51:16.200
the time to go from
established to fixation.

00:51:16.200 --> 00:51:17.992
So it's actually the
next time scale there.

00:51:17.992 --> 00:51:19.699
And actually, the time
to get established

00:51:19.699 --> 00:51:20.770
is actually rather short.

00:51:23.240 --> 00:51:25.740
So a mutation appears, and most
of the time it goes extinct.

00:51:25.740 --> 00:51:27.531
But the ones that don't
go extinct actually

00:51:27.531 --> 00:51:29.570
get established rather
quickly, because that's

00:51:29.570 --> 00:51:33.190
a biased sampling
over the trajectories.

00:51:33.190 --> 00:51:35.360
But there is a rather
significant time

00:51:35.360 --> 00:51:37.192
that it takes for
the lineage to go

00:51:37.192 --> 00:51:38.900
from being established
to actually fixing

00:51:38.900 --> 00:51:39.710
in the population.

00:51:39.710 --> 00:51:42.300
So this is kind of how long
it takes for a mutation

00:51:42.300 --> 00:51:45.220
to take over a population.

00:51:45.220 --> 00:51:47.500
We might call this the
time to spread or so.

00:51:50.870 --> 00:51:52.920
And it turns out
that that time--

00:51:52.920 --> 00:51:55.710
what is it going to depend on?

00:51:55.710 --> 00:51:56.489
AUDIENCE: s.

00:51:56.489 --> 00:51:58.030
PROFESSOR: It's
going to depend on s.

00:51:58.030 --> 00:52:04.610
So as s goes up,
then this goes down.

00:52:04.610 --> 00:52:05.410
All right, perfect.

00:52:05.410 --> 00:52:09.124
All right, let's just
go put a 1 over s there.

00:52:09.124 --> 00:52:11.290
And this is because it's
going to grow exponentially

00:52:11.290 --> 00:52:13.190
in the population.

00:52:13.190 --> 00:52:15.560
And then how else is
it going to depend on?

00:52:15.560 --> 00:52:16.860
AUDIENCE: n.

00:52:16.860 --> 00:52:18.100
PROFESSOR: n, right.

00:52:18.100 --> 00:52:22.980
And indeed, this is going
to be the log of n times s.

00:52:22.980 --> 00:52:25.460
It's really n over
n established.

00:52:25.460 --> 00:52:28.280
Because the idea is that you
start out at n established.

00:52:28.280 --> 00:52:30.920
You grow exponentially with
rate s until you kind of take

00:52:30.920 --> 00:52:32.780
over the population, size n.

00:52:36.215 --> 00:52:41.846
And this s appears because
it's 1 over n established.

00:52:41.846 --> 00:52:44.230
Because this in the log
is really the population

00:52:44.230 --> 00:52:45.480
size divided by n established.

00:52:48.030 --> 00:52:50.470
So this is one time scale.

00:52:50.470 --> 00:52:52.810
Do you guys understand why
it should be like this?

00:52:57.060 --> 00:52:57.560
Right.

00:52:57.560 --> 00:52:59.768
And what's the other time
scale that's relevant here?

00:52:59.768 --> 00:53:03.530
AUDIENCE: How fast
mutations occur.

00:53:03.530 --> 00:53:06.536
PROFESSOR: How fast
mutations-- yes.

00:53:06.536 --> 00:53:08.744
AUDIENCE: How long you have
to wait from one mutation

00:53:08.744 --> 00:53:09.950
to the next mutation.

00:53:09.950 --> 00:53:10.770
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:53:10.770 --> 00:53:14.370
So this is how long you have
to wait for one mutation.

00:53:14.370 --> 00:53:20.290
So this is T, what we
might call T mutation.

00:53:20.290 --> 00:53:21.850
Now it's a little
bit subtle to think

00:53:21.850 --> 00:53:25.440
about what this should be.

00:53:25.440 --> 00:53:27.940
But it should say
something about the time

00:53:27.940 --> 00:53:32.216
it takes for mutations to
appear in the population.

00:53:32.216 --> 00:53:36.430
So let's go ahead and just
guess what this might be.

00:53:36.430 --> 00:53:38.720
T mutation should
be equal to what?

00:53:38.720 --> 00:53:40.380
All right, so it could be--

00:53:45.800 --> 00:53:46.716
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:52.754 --> 00:53:53.420
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:53:53.420 --> 00:53:56.650
So I guess I'm trying to get you
to think about what this should

00:53:56.650 --> 00:53:59.860
mean to be relevant for
determining the time

00:53:59.860 --> 00:54:02.022
scales of whether clonal
interference is important.

00:54:02.022 --> 00:54:04.170
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:04.170 --> 00:54:08.820
PROFESSOR: Mu is the
probability per generation

00:54:08.820 --> 00:54:13.020
of having a beneficial
mutation of magnitude s.

00:54:13.020 --> 00:54:18.764
Mu is kind of the mutation rate.

00:54:18.764 --> 00:54:20.442
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:20.442 --> 00:54:21.150
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:54:21.150 --> 00:54:23.839
But we'll just
assume that there's

00:54:23.839 --> 00:54:25.380
only one kind of
beneficial mutation,

00:54:25.380 --> 00:54:28.550
and every beneficial
mutation has magnitude s,

00:54:28.550 --> 00:54:30.990
for simplicity.

00:54:30.990 --> 00:54:32.960
So it's mutation rate.

00:54:32.960 --> 00:54:35.430
It's a beneficial mutation
rate per generation

00:54:35.430 --> 00:54:36.965
of leading to mutation s.

00:54:43.040 --> 00:54:46.720
And you can just also say,
if you have no idea what

00:54:46.720 --> 00:54:49.160
I'm talking about, it's fine.

00:54:49.160 --> 00:54:52.890
But it's worth spending a
little bit of time thinking

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:54.880
about what should
be the relevant time

00:54:54.880 --> 00:54:57.466
scale to compare to this.

00:54:57.466 --> 00:54:57.965
Yes?

00:54:57.965 --> 00:55:00.212
AUDIENCE: So Mu is per
organism [INAUDIBLE]?

00:55:03.156 --> 00:55:04.156
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:55:16.990 --> 00:55:18.970
And it's OK if you
find this confusing,

00:55:18.970 --> 00:55:20.200
because this is subtle.

00:55:20.200 --> 00:55:22.380
But if you think about
it for 30 seconds, then

00:55:22.380 --> 00:55:27.220
maybe you'll be fertile ground
for the discussion to follow.

00:55:47.392 --> 00:55:49.920
All right, let's go ahead and
vote and see where we are.

00:55:49.920 --> 00:55:53.220
Ready, three, two, one.

00:55:56.020 --> 00:55:58.260
All right.

00:55:58.260 --> 00:55:59.850
This is very nice.

00:55:59.850 --> 00:56:05.748
Almost everybody is saying C.
Although it really should be D.

00:56:05.748 --> 00:56:06.664
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:09.800 --> 00:56:12.594
So 1 over s is units of time,
and 1 over mu is [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:15.790 --> 00:56:19.110
PROFESSOR: OK, that's an
interesting statement.

00:56:19.110 --> 00:56:21.730
I mean, I guess this
is a relative fitness.

00:56:21.730 --> 00:56:22.690
AUDIENCE: So s is mu.

00:56:23.279 --> 00:56:25.070
AUDIENCE: But right
there, you have s units

00:56:25.070 --> 00:56:29.000
of time, 1/s units of time.

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:30.625
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so
the problem of this

00:56:30.625 --> 00:56:33.525
is this is all in units
of generation time.

00:56:33.525 --> 00:56:34.900
Because this is
really telling us

00:56:34.900 --> 00:56:36.233
about the number of generations.

00:56:39.970 --> 00:56:45.379
So what is going on?

00:56:45.379 --> 00:56:47.420
Because 1 over mu n should
also be a time, right?

00:56:49.990 --> 00:56:50.906
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:57:00.800 --> 00:57:02.380
Yeah, I'm not sure
if-- yeah, I mean,

00:57:02.380 --> 00:57:03.754
since this is all
in generations,

00:57:03.754 --> 00:57:11.550
I'm not sure if we even have
to-- yeah, I think it's OK.

00:57:11.550 --> 00:57:13.494
AUDIENCE: n times s
has to be [INAUDIBLE].

00:57:16.410 --> 00:57:18.880
PROFESSOR: I like
that statement.

00:57:18.880 --> 00:57:20.100
But then he, I mean--

00:57:20.100 --> 00:57:21.940
AUDIENCE: Well, then
you have 1 over mu.

00:57:21.940 --> 00:57:22.939
PROFESSOR: Yeah, I know.

00:57:22.939 --> 00:57:25.845
But then, this should
have units of time.

00:57:25.845 --> 00:57:29.520
I agree with your statement, but
I also sort of agree with his,

00:57:29.520 --> 00:57:30.520
the 1 over s here.

00:57:30.520 --> 00:57:31.190
You know that's the problem.

00:57:31.190 --> 00:57:32.130
AUDIENCE: Everything
is basically unitless.

00:57:32.130 --> 00:57:33.630
PROFESSOR: Yeah, but I
think that it's really

00:57:33.630 --> 00:57:35.463
because everything's
in units of generation.

00:57:35.463 --> 00:57:37.300
So really, it's all
unitless, except for mu.

00:57:37.300 --> 00:57:38.166
Yeah.

00:57:38.166 --> 00:57:39.541
AUDIENCE: What I
don't understand

00:57:39.541 --> 00:57:44.462
is why how beneficial
the mutation is

00:57:44.462 --> 00:57:46.430
should play into how--

00:57:46.430 --> 00:57:47.860
PROFESSOR: No, I agree.

00:57:47.860 --> 00:57:49.900
This is subtle.

00:57:49.900 --> 00:57:51.460
So let's imagine this is time.

00:57:55.700 --> 00:58:01.330
Now, 1 over mu n is
telling us how much time

00:58:01.330 --> 00:58:03.660
there is between the
initial appearance

00:58:03.660 --> 00:58:06.994
of these beneficial mutants.

00:58:06.994 --> 00:58:08.535
So here we get a
beneficial mutation.

00:58:10.484 --> 00:58:12.150
But what do you think
is going to happen

00:58:12.150 --> 00:58:14.754
to that beneficial mutation?

00:58:14.754 --> 00:58:15.670
Yeah, that guy's dead.

00:58:15.670 --> 00:58:18.709
It comes up.

00:58:18.709 --> 00:58:21.250
How long do we have to wait for
the next beneficial mutation?

00:58:21.250 --> 00:58:22.280
AUDIENCE: 1 over mu n.

00:58:22.280 --> 00:58:23.238
PROFESSOR: 1 over mu n.

00:58:23.238 --> 00:58:24.824
Is it going to be exactly that?

00:58:24.824 --> 00:58:26.240
Is going to be
peaked around that?

00:58:29.460 --> 00:58:31.790
All right, verbal
answer, what is

00:58:31.790 --> 00:58:34.070
going to be the
probability distribution

00:58:34.070 --> 00:58:38.490
between successive appearances
of this beneficial mutation?

00:58:38.490 --> 00:58:40.996
Ready, three, two, one.

00:58:40.996 --> 00:58:41.912
AUDIENCE: Exponential.

00:58:41.912 --> 00:58:44.130
PROFESSOR: It's
exponentially distributed.

00:58:44.130 --> 00:58:46.010
So there might be another one
that's coming through here.

00:58:46.010 --> 00:58:47.090
What do you think is going
to happen to that guy?

00:58:47.090 --> 00:58:47.842
AUDIENCE: Probably dead.

00:58:47.842 --> 00:58:48.950
PROFESSOR: Oh, he's dead.

00:58:48.950 --> 00:58:50.330
OK.

00:58:50.330 --> 00:58:51.880
Another one.

00:58:51.880 --> 00:58:54.900
So these guys are appearing.

00:58:54.900 --> 00:58:57.360
But if the magnitude
of s is, say,

00:58:57.360 --> 00:58:59.770
0.02, that means we have to
wait for 50 of these things

00:58:59.770 --> 00:59:01.890
to appear before we
expect that one of them

00:59:01.890 --> 00:59:05.250
is actually going
to get established.

00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:07.460
And established means
it gets up to 1 over s.

00:59:12.342 --> 00:59:13.800
So this guy, once
he's established,

00:59:13.800 --> 00:59:17.560
he's going to grow
exponentially in the population.

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:24.760
But the idea is that the time
scale here of 1 over mu n

00:59:24.760 --> 00:59:27.810
is the time between
successive appearances

00:59:27.810 --> 00:59:36.980
of this beneficial mutation,
whereas as 1 over mu ns

00:59:36.980 --> 00:59:41.030
is the time scale between
successive establishments

00:59:41.030 --> 00:59:42.380
of these beneficial mutations.

00:59:42.380 --> 00:59:43.921
And it's only if
they get established

00:59:43.921 --> 00:59:47.060
that they're relevant.

00:59:47.060 --> 00:59:52.740
So that's why the t mutation
established is 1 over mu ns.

00:59:56.320 --> 01:00:02.710
Now, no clonal interference
means that one of these

01:00:02.710 --> 01:00:04.150
is larger than the other one.

01:00:07.490 --> 01:00:10.340
So no clonal
interference means is it,

01:00:10.340 --> 01:00:13.470
A, this guy's larger,
or B, this guy's larger?

01:00:16.370 --> 01:00:18.431
So larger, question mark.

01:00:18.431 --> 01:00:18.930
This one?

01:00:18.930 --> 01:00:19.730
That one?

01:00:19.730 --> 01:00:21.521
All right, think about
this for 15 seconds,

01:00:21.521 --> 01:00:24.160
just to make sure that
we're-- make sure.

01:00:24.160 --> 01:00:26.210
We're asking, if there's
no clonal interference,

01:00:26.210 --> 01:00:28.751
it means that one of these is
much larger than the other one.

01:00:28.751 --> 01:00:29.350
Which one?

01:00:29.350 --> 01:00:34.140
Ready, three, two, one.

01:00:34.140 --> 01:00:39.370
It means that this thing is
much larger than this one.

01:00:39.370 --> 01:00:46.820
So this thing has to be much
larger than t establish to fix.

01:00:49.980 --> 01:00:53.030
Because if it's the
case this time scale

01:00:53.030 --> 01:00:55.460
is very large compared to
this time scale of spreading,

01:00:55.460 --> 01:00:58.280
then the mutations don't
ever clonal interfere.

01:01:01.840 --> 01:01:04.500
I think it's very important
that you can reconstruct

01:01:04.500 --> 01:01:08.230
this whole argument
because it has

01:01:08.230 --> 01:01:10.690
all the ingredients of
the dynamics in terms

01:01:10.690 --> 01:01:14.235
of stochastic, and
then deterministic.

01:01:16.930 --> 01:01:20.290
If you find this stuff
confusing, please

01:01:20.290 --> 01:01:22.940
go through it with a friend
or come to me after class.

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:28.570
So what we went to do
for the last 20 minutes

01:01:28.570 --> 01:01:32.680
is, then, talk
about Roy's paper.

01:01:32.680 --> 01:01:37.796
And I think that this paper
is interesting and subtle.

01:01:37.796 --> 01:01:39.670
It's a little bit hard
to tell how much of it

01:01:39.670 --> 01:01:45.020
is an experimental kind of
straight up demonstration

01:01:45.020 --> 01:01:47.350
or how much of it is that
it's just a way of getting

01:01:47.350 --> 01:01:49.179
you to think new thoughts.

01:01:49.179 --> 01:01:51.470
It certainly is a way to get
you to think new thoughts.

01:01:51.470 --> 01:01:54.990
At least I felt that it
had that effect on me,

01:01:54.990 --> 01:01:57.510
and that after
reading it, I just

01:01:57.510 --> 01:01:59.620
got very excited
about all the dynamics

01:01:59.620 --> 01:02:03.670
that were at play
here, and how out

01:02:03.670 --> 01:02:05.660
of the complexity of
this clonal interference

01:02:05.660 --> 01:02:07.270
process, maybe, in
some cases, there

01:02:07.270 --> 01:02:10.060
might be some even simpler
phenomenological type

01:02:10.060 --> 01:02:12.164
description of
what was going on.

01:02:12.164 --> 01:02:14.580
But I think that what is very
interesting about that paper

01:02:14.580 --> 01:02:17.210
is this idea that what they
really wanted to measure

01:02:17.210 --> 01:02:19.140
was this probability
distribution

01:02:19.140 --> 01:02:22.200
of beneficial mutations.

01:02:22.200 --> 01:02:25.874
So what we mean by that is that
different beneficial mutations

01:02:25.874 --> 01:02:27.040
will have different effects.

01:02:36.790 --> 01:02:40.350
And in particular, you could
imagine a thought experiment

01:02:40.350 --> 01:02:43.480
where you take an E. coli cell.

01:02:43.480 --> 01:02:49.770
How big is the E.
coli genome roughly?

01:02:49.770 --> 01:02:52.685
And just like it's always good
to have guideposts for how long

01:02:52.685 --> 01:02:54.935
ago things happened, it's
also good to have guideposts

01:02:54.935 --> 01:02:56.860
for things like it's
just good to have

01:02:56.860 --> 01:03:00.590
a few genome sizes memorized.

01:03:00.590 --> 01:03:02.300
Now does anybody know
the E. coli genome?

01:03:02.300 --> 01:03:04.474
AUDIENCE: 2,000 base pairs.

