AUDIENCE: 2,000 [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:07.485 --> 01:03:10.330
PROFESSOR: No, I just want to
make sure that we're-- yeah.

01:03:10.330 --> 01:03:13.800
Yeah, it's a bit more than that.

01:03:13.800 --> 01:03:16.000
It's a few million base
pairs, three or four,

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:18.100
depending on the strain.

01:03:18.100 --> 01:03:21.190
But you can imagine a thought
experiment where you go in,

01:03:21.190 --> 01:03:26.490
and at every base pair you
make the three possible point

01:03:26.490 --> 01:03:28.120
mutations.

01:03:28.120 --> 01:03:31.700
So then you can imagine having
10 million different strains

01:03:31.700 --> 01:03:35.020
that are each
different at one site.

01:03:35.020 --> 01:03:39.310
And then what we can do is we
can plot the rate of population

01:03:39.310 --> 01:03:41.510
growth in some environment.

01:03:41.510 --> 01:03:43.810
So this is gamma.

01:03:43.810 --> 01:03:51.040
It's the 1 over n dn/dt,
basically division, right?

01:03:51.040 --> 01:03:59.110
Normalized by the
wild type division.

01:03:59.110 --> 01:04:04.070
I'm sorry, that's
supposed to be down there.

01:04:04.070 --> 01:04:08.970
So this is gamma over
gamma of wild type.

01:04:08.970 --> 01:04:15.510
And this could be E. coli
in LB or minimal media or at

01:04:15.510 --> 01:04:16.040
30 [? ci ?].

01:04:16.040 --> 01:04:19.260
You pick some
reasonable environment.

01:04:19.260 --> 01:04:21.440
Question is, if you draw
the histogram of what

01:04:21.440 --> 01:04:24.265
this thing should look
like, what should it be?

01:04:29.390 --> 01:04:32.960
Now what I'm going to ask
you to do is, in 30 seconds,

01:04:32.960 --> 01:04:35.490
draw something on
your sheet of paper.

01:04:38.014 --> 01:04:39.430
This is supposed
to be a frequency

01:04:39.430 --> 01:04:45.107
or histogram over those 10
million point mutations.

01:04:45.107 --> 01:04:46.940
So we haven't actually
done this experiment.

01:04:46.940 --> 01:04:54.160
But I think we have
made all possible gene

01:04:54.160 --> 01:05:01.910
knockouts in E. coli, so
removing each of the genes.

01:05:01.910 --> 01:05:03.540
And we've done that in E. coli.

01:05:03.540 --> 01:05:04.822
We've done it in yeast.

01:05:04.822 --> 01:05:07.280
And indeed, in yeast, they're
actually making and measuring

01:05:07.280 --> 01:05:11.270
the division rate for
all pairwise knockouts.

01:05:11.270 --> 01:05:14.600
So they're some fraction
of the way through.

01:05:14.600 --> 01:05:17.315
They published their first
10 million measurements

01:05:17.315 --> 01:05:19.690
for the division rate of the
pairwise knockouts in yeast.

01:05:19.690 --> 01:05:21.350
This is Charlie
Boone at Toronto.

01:05:21.350 --> 01:05:23.630
It's an amazing data set.

01:05:23.630 --> 01:05:25.000
Sorry, this is a simpler one.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:27.850
So this is just if we make
a histogram of the growth

01:05:27.850 --> 01:05:33.530
rate of E. coli, all 10
million possible point

01:05:33.530 --> 01:05:35.279
mutations in E.
coli, what do you

01:05:35.279 --> 01:05:36.528
think it's going to look like?

