01:06:21.415 --> 01:06:22.290
PROFESSOR: All right.

01:06:22.290 --> 01:06:24.248
And what I find interesting
about this exercise

01:06:24.248 --> 01:06:26.440
is that you get all
possible distributions.

01:06:30.276 --> 01:06:34.530
No, but it's funny, because it's
like a super basic question.

01:06:34.530 --> 01:06:38.800
And somehow we don't necessarily
think about it, or whatnot.

01:06:38.800 --> 01:06:40.250
Could somebody
throw out what they

01:06:40.250 --> 01:06:41.976
think maybe should be going on?

01:06:41.976 --> 01:06:42.928
Yeah.

01:06:42.928 --> 01:06:46.736
AUDIENCE: So I'm expecting
