01:07:25.478 --> 01:07:26.311
PROFESSOR: Yeah, OK.

01:07:26.311 --> 01:07:28.970
So lots of them, maybe.

01:07:28.970 --> 01:07:31.630
So these are the two
polar views of the world,

01:07:31.630 --> 01:07:35.225
that nothing matters,
or you're all dead.

01:07:37.737 --> 01:07:39.320
AUDIENCE: I think
it can reconcile it.

01:07:39.320 --> 01:07:41.240
I think you can say--

01:07:41.240 --> 01:07:45.040
PROFESSOR: OK, well, now I
think you're being too-- OK,

01:07:45.040 --> 01:07:46.510
how are we going
to reconcile them?

01:07:46.510 --> 01:07:48.551
AUDIENCE: So we know that
there's the [? third ?]

01:07:48.551 --> 01:07:49.644
[? bubble, ?] right?

01:07:49.644 --> 01:07:50.310
PROFESSOR: Sure.

01:07:50.310 --> 01:07:53.572
AUDIENCE: And so there's
probably at least 1/3

01:07:53.572 --> 01:07:57.486
somewhere it just doesn't
matter at all, where

01:07:57.486 --> 01:07:59.014
you get the same code.

01:07:59.014 --> 01:08:00.930
PROFESSOR: Although there
are cases, actually,

01:08:00.930 --> 01:08:02.660
where even silent
mutations end up changing

01:08:02.660 --> 01:08:03.951
protein at an expression level.

01:08:03.951 --> 01:08:07.056
All right, but I don't
know if this reconciles

01:08:07.056 --> 01:08:08.180
the two views of the world.

01:08:12.520 --> 01:08:18.135
So some people have drawn
things that look like this.

01:08:18.135 --> 01:08:21.090
Some people will draw it,
and things look like this.

01:08:21.090 --> 01:08:22.056
Yeah.

01:08:22.056 --> 01:08:23.514
And we have a
uniform distribution.

01:08:27.029 --> 01:08:30.069
If you're going to make a null
model, I mean, I don't know.

01:08:30.069 --> 01:08:32.630
So I would say that we
have enough information

01:08:32.630 --> 01:08:35.290
to say something about what
this thing should look like.

01:08:38.340 --> 01:08:43.695
So first of all, some fraction
of genes are indeed essential.

01:08:49.300 --> 01:08:53.430
For 10% or 20% of the genes,
you remove it, the cell is dead.

01:08:53.430 --> 01:08:56.340
That doesn't mean that 10%
to 20% of point mutations

01:08:56.340 --> 01:08:59.420
will lead to a lethal
phenotype, but it

01:08:59.420 --> 01:09:05.359
means that if you do inactivate
or knock out that gene,

01:09:05.359 --> 01:09:06.979
then it will be lethal.

01:09:06.979 --> 01:09:12.547
So that means that there are
indeed some set of these point

01:09:12.547 --> 01:09:14.130
mutations that are
going to be lethal,

01:09:14.130 --> 01:09:17.720
but it's going to be small.

01:09:17.720 --> 01:09:19.710
And I don't know what
the actual number

01:09:19.710 --> 01:09:29.040
would be, but maybe 1 in 10
to the 4, something small.

01:09:29.040 --> 01:09:34.270
Because it's probably only
10% the locations on the gene

01:09:34.270 --> 01:09:35.590
would actually knock it out.

01:09:35.590 --> 01:09:37.100
I'm making up that number.

01:09:37.100 --> 01:09:39.640
The protein guys would
have a much better sense.

01:09:39.640 --> 01:09:41.439
But it's going to
be a small number.

01:09:41.439 --> 01:09:43.410
It might only be 1% of
the mutations, actually,

01:09:43.410 --> 01:09:46.140
would actually knock out
the function of the protein.

01:09:46.140 --> 01:09:49.690
And then not all of the genome
actually codes for proteins.

01:09:49.690 --> 01:09:51.689
So you start multiplying
small numbers together,

01:09:51.689 --> 01:09:53.439
and you get something
that's rather small.

01:09:53.439 --> 01:09:55.810
But there will be some
number of mutations there.

01:09:55.810 --> 01:09:57.640
However, the vast
majority of mutations

01:09:57.640 --> 01:10:00.780
will have no measurable
fitness effect.

01:10:00.780 --> 01:10:06.600
So indeed, this thing kind
of peaks here, and then

01:10:06.600 --> 01:10:07.880
rather sharply comes down.

01:10:07.880 --> 01:10:12.440
And this is on a linear
scale, or something like that.

01:10:12.440 --> 01:10:15.680
So the width might
indeed be a few percent.

01:10:20.210 --> 01:10:23.480
But actually, probably
even less, maybe 1%,

01:10:23.480 --> 01:10:26.182
or half, something small.

01:10:26.182 --> 01:10:26.682
Yeah.

01:10:26.682 --> 01:10:29.670
AUDIENCE: How skewed is it?

01:10:29.670 --> 01:10:32.205
PROFESSOR: So on a linear
scale, it doesn't look skewed.

01:10:32.205 --> 01:10:34.120
On a log scale, I think it does.

01:10:34.120 --> 01:10:36.550
I mean, in the sense that
if you plot log frequency

01:10:36.550 --> 01:10:38.700
on this axis, then
there's a longer tail

01:10:38.700 --> 01:10:40.520
on the left than on the right.

01:10:40.520 --> 01:10:44.350
But I'd say on a linear scale,
it's just pretty sharp function

01:10:44.350 --> 01:10:44.850
there.

01:10:44.850 --> 01:10:46.475
AUDIENCE: So people
have measured that?

01:10:47.990 --> 01:10:50.760
PROFESSOR: Certainly for
all the gene knockouts,

01:10:50.760 --> 01:10:52.080
we have measured this.

01:10:52.080 --> 01:10:55.980
And even that distribution
is sharply peaked.

01:10:55.980 --> 01:10:58.570
So the point mutation
distribution's

01:10:58.570 --> 01:11:00.926
going to be even
more tightly peaked.

01:11:00.926 --> 01:11:02.509
AUDIENCE: For most
genes, you can just

01:11:02.509 --> 01:11:04.284
knock them out and [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:04.284 --> 01:11:04.950
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:11:04.950 --> 01:11:05.450
Sorry.

01:11:05.450 --> 01:11:07.990
So for most genes, at least
in many environments--

01:11:07.990 --> 01:11:10.406
and of course, it depends on
what environment you measure.

01:11:10.406 --> 01:11:12.420
But for most genes,
you can knock them out.

01:11:12.420 --> 01:11:14.670
Certainly in rich media,
most genes you can knock out.

01:11:23.790 --> 01:11:31.400
This, as I said, might be
1 in 10 to the minus 3, 4.

01:11:35.210 --> 01:11:37.770
I might be off by a couple
orders of magnitude.

01:11:37.770 --> 01:11:40.950
But the point is that this is
a small fraction over here.

01:11:40.950 --> 01:11:41.612
Most are here.

01:11:41.612 --> 01:11:44.070
And there will be some point
mutations that come down here.

01:11:44.070 --> 01:11:46.210
But on a linear scale, it's
going to be very small.

01:11:51.160 --> 01:11:53.270
Now from the standpoint
of a population evolving

01:11:53.270 --> 01:11:55.490
to a new environment,
which mutations

01:11:55.490 --> 01:11:57.292
are we most interested in?

01:11:57.292 --> 01:11:58.600
AUDIENCE: The beneficial.

01:11:58.600 --> 01:12:00.099
PROFESSOR: The
beneficial mutations.

01:12:00.099 --> 01:12:02.840
So we're most interested
in these guys.

01:12:05.870 --> 01:12:09.250
And indeed, this
is the distribution

01:12:09.250 --> 01:12:14.120
that [INAUDIBLE] set out to try
and measure in that experiment

01:12:14.120 --> 01:12:17.180
that we just read
about last night.

01:12:17.180 --> 01:12:19.840
So he wanted to know,
if you zoom in here--

01:12:19.840 --> 01:12:22.400
because remember, this is even
narrower than I've actually

01:12:22.400 --> 01:12:24.400
drawn.

01:12:24.400 --> 01:12:28.320
But this distribution,
the probability

01:12:28.320 --> 01:12:32.110
of a beneficial mutation
of magnitude s-- s, here 0,

01:12:32.110 --> 01:12:36.555
s-- it's going to do something.

01:12:39.240 --> 01:12:40.915
Many mutations that
are nearly neutral,

01:12:40.915 --> 01:12:42.540
but it's going to
fall off in some way,

01:12:42.540 --> 01:12:44.660
and they wanted to
try and measure this.

01:12:44.660 --> 01:12:48.190
Now how many mutations
confer a 2% advantage, 4%,

01:12:48.190 --> 01:12:49.690
for this particular
E. coli strain

01:12:49.690 --> 01:12:52.810
in that particular environment?

01:12:52.810 --> 01:12:55.874
But it turned out being
difficult to measure.

01:12:55.874 --> 01:12:57.790
And what was the reason
that they gave for why

01:12:57.790 --> 01:12:58.956
it was difficult to measure?

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:06.540
Somebody?

01:13:06.540 --> 01:13:07.201
Anybody?

01:13:07.201 --> 01:13:07.700
Please?

01:13:16.208 --> 01:13:17.124
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:13:21.526 --> 01:13:22.150
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:13:22.150 --> 01:13:23.691
But the equivalence
principle doesn't

01:13:23.691 --> 01:13:26.860
say that they're all
equivalent necessarily.

01:13:26.860 --> 01:13:31.523
AUDIENCE: Well, you can
make different [INAUDIBLE].

01:13:31.523 --> 01:13:33.064
So there are different
distributions,

01:13:33.064 --> 01:13:35.530
and they each have
their perimeters

01:13:35.530 --> 01:13:36.199
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:13:36.199 --> 01:13:37.574
AUDIENCE: You can
pick perimeters

01:13:37.574 --> 01:13:43.140
for each of them, such that
they will give you the same--

01:13:43.140 --> 01:13:44.570
PROFESSOR: OK, that's right.

01:13:44.570 --> 01:13:47.440
So what they found was
that different underlying

01:13:47.440 --> 01:13:50.724
distributions-- this
probability distribution

01:13:50.724 --> 01:13:52.140
for beneficial
mutations, function

01:13:52.140 --> 01:13:55.200
of s-- different
underlying distributions

01:13:55.200 --> 01:13:58.570
could give you the same final
output in their measurements.

01:13:58.570 --> 01:13:59.430
But why was that?

01:14:05.850 --> 01:14:06.560
Yeah, John?

01:14:06.560 --> 01:14:09.162
AUDIENCE: The only thing you
can measure is what fixes.

01:14:09.162 --> 01:14:09.870
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:14:09.870 --> 01:14:13.590
So you can only
measure what it fixes,

01:14:13.590 --> 01:14:17.130
or becomes significant
fraction population, 10%.

01:14:17.130 --> 01:14:18.805
Only measure what
fixes or grows.

01:14:22.520 --> 01:14:25.442
And what does that mean?

01:14:25.442 --> 01:14:29.292
AUDIENCE: Well, it means that
you're not probing [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:29.292 --> 01:14:30.000
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:14:30.000 --> 01:14:32.484
It means that we're not probing
that distribution, and why not?

01:14:32.484 --> 01:14:33.400
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:36.064 --> 01:14:36.730
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:14:36.730 --> 01:14:39.105
But why is it that we only
see part of this distribution?

01:14:39.105 --> 01:14:40.520
What was their--

01:14:40.520 --> 01:14:42.510
AUDIENCE: We don't see
the ones that die out.

01:14:42.510 --> 01:14:44.426
PROFESSOR: We don't see
the ones that die out.

01:14:44.426 --> 01:14:46.430
And why is that they die out?

01:14:46.430 --> 01:14:48.055
Or why is it that they--

01:14:48.055 --> 01:14:49.270
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:49.270 --> 01:14:52.540
PROFESSOR: OK, yeah.

01:14:52.540 --> 01:14:53.200
Yes.

01:14:53.200 --> 01:14:54.699
So the fact of
stochastic extinction

01:14:54.699 --> 01:14:55.790
is very relevant here.

01:14:55.790 --> 01:14:57.790
And I think that in this
paper they a little bit

01:14:57.790 --> 01:15:01.250
underplay that aspect of it,
because they're primarily

01:15:01.250 --> 01:15:03.410
arguing that it was
another effect that led

01:15:03.410 --> 01:15:05.680
to this equivalence principle.

01:15:05.680 --> 01:15:06.924
Right?

01:15:06.924 --> 01:15:07.890
AUDIENCE: Competition.

01:15:07.890 --> 01:15:09.060
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
clonal interference.

01:15:09.060 --> 01:15:11.101
I mean, that's why we
spent the last hour talking

01:15:11.101 --> 01:15:12.780
about clonal interference.

01:15:12.780 --> 01:15:14.870
So their argument
in this paper was

01:15:14.870 --> 01:15:16.950
that, as a result of
clonal interference,

01:15:16.950 --> 01:15:19.960
competition between
these different lineages,

01:15:19.960 --> 01:15:22.280
then the distribution
of fitness effects

01:15:22.280 --> 01:15:24.350
that you measure,
that fix, is not

01:15:24.350 --> 01:15:26.600
the distribution that was
the underlying distribution.

01:15:29.210 --> 01:15:34.240
Because less fit beneficial
mutations get out-competed.

01:15:34.240 --> 01:15:35.850
But there's a very
important question,

01:15:35.850 --> 01:15:41.540
which is, let's imagine
that let's have mu go to 0.

01:15:44.550 --> 01:15:46.060
Or we go to small populations.

01:15:46.060 --> 01:15:50.250
Let's say that after
reading his paper

01:15:50.250 --> 01:15:52.690
I said, OK, well, yeah,
because of clonal interference

01:15:52.690 --> 01:15:55.829
I can't measure this probability
distribution in the set up

01:15:55.829 --> 01:15:56.370
that he used.

01:15:56.370 --> 01:15:59.300
But maybe if I go to
small population sizes,

01:15:59.300 --> 01:16:03.280
or I reduce the mutation
rate somehow-- magic--

01:16:03.280 --> 01:16:07.850
then would this allow me to
measure that distribution?

01:16:07.850 --> 01:16:09.470
So I'm going to ask
you guys to vote.

01:16:09.470 --> 01:16:10.370
So mu, let's say.

01:16:10.370 --> 01:16:12.470
Our experiment, I
have mu go to 0.

01:16:12.470 --> 01:16:16.990
Does this mean that when
I then go do write CFP,

01:16:16.990 --> 01:16:21.610
YFP, they're 50-50, and
then you start doing this.

01:16:21.610 --> 01:16:25.227
And we measure the
slope to get s,

01:16:25.227 --> 01:16:26.435
just like in this experiment.

01:16:29.085 --> 01:16:38.100
If I plot the distribution
of resulting s's, no clonal

01:16:38.100 --> 01:16:41.660
interference anymore, because
I've set mu equal to 0.

01:16:41.660 --> 01:16:45.160
So this thing goes to infinity.

01:16:45.160 --> 01:16:50.710
Do I recover the
underlying distribution?

01:16:50.710 --> 01:16:51.710
Ready.

01:16:51.710 --> 01:16:57.210
So P be measured,
as a function of s,

01:16:57.210 --> 01:17:00.380
is it equal to the true one?

01:17:00.380 --> 01:17:01.080
Question mark.

